#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/applications.md savings=3%
M|Lean|tx|The Lean Startup was born in Silicon Valley software startups, but its principles apply wherever there is uncertainty abt what to bd, who to bd it for, or how to bd a sustainable business. The core loop (bd-Measure-Learn) and the core mindset (validate assumptions w/ the smallest possible investment) translate across industries, organization tp, and pd categories. The specific tactics, however, must be adapted to each context.
M|Lean|tx|SaaS is the natural home for lean methodology. Short iteration cycles, measurable us behavior, and flexible dpl make SaaS ideal for rapid experimentation.
M|Step|**Ph|Problem Validation (Weeks 1-3)**
M|Step|it|[ ] Identify 30 potential cs in the target segment
M|Step|it|[ ] Conduct 15-20 problem discovery interviews
M|Step|it|[ ] Map the current workflow and pain points
M|Step|it|[ ] Identify the #1 unmet need (the "hair on fire" problem)
M|Step|it|[ ] Write the value hypothesis
M|Step|**Ph|Solution Validation (Weeks 4-8)**
M|Step|it|[ ] cr a landing page describing the solution w/ pricing
M|Step|- [ |3-5% em capture)
M|Step|it|[ ] bd a concierge or Wizard of Oz MVP for 5-10 engaged prospects
M|Step|it|[ ] Deliver the service manually; observe behavior and gather feedback
M|Step|it|[ ] Validate willingness to pay (charge or get letters of intent)
M|Step|**Ph|pd bd and Iteration (Weeks 9-16)**
M|Step|it|[ ] bd the single-feature MVP based on concierge learnings
M|Step|it|[ ] Launch to 20-50 beta us w/ full instrumentation
M|Step|it|[ ] Measure activation rate, Day-7 retention, and core feature usage
M|Step|it|[ ] Run weekly bd-Measure-Learn loops on the biggest engagement gap
M|Step|it|[ ] Conduct 5 us interviews per week alongside quantitative data
M|Step|**Ph|pd-mk Fit Assessment (Weeks 17-24)**
M|Step|it|[ ] Administer Sean Ellis survey ("How wld you feel if you cld no longer use this pd?")
M|Step|- [ |40%+ respond "very disappointed"
M|Step|it|[ ] Measure Month-1 retention by cohort (target varies by category)
M|Step|- [ |LTV/CAC ratio above 3:1
M|Step|it|[ ] If not hitting targets, identify whether to pivot or persevere
M|SaaS|tx|\| Stage \| Primary Metrics \| Decision Trigger \|
M|SaaS|tx|\|-------\|----------------\|-----------------\|
M|SaaS|tx|\| Pre-launch \| Landing page conversion, interview qual signals \| Below 2% conversion = rethink positioning \|
M|SaaS|tx|\| Beta \| Activation rate, Day-7 retention, feature usage \| Below 30% activation = fix onboarding \|
M|SaaS|tx|\| Early growth \| MRR, churn rate, NPS \| Above 10% monthly churn = fix value delivery \|
M|SaaS|tx|\| Scale \| LTV/CAC, net rv retention, payback period \| LTV/CAC below 3 = fix economics before scaling \|
M|Lean|Larg|bureaucracy, risk aversion, competing priorities, and the temptation to apply existing processes to fundamentally uncertain work.
M|The |tx|cr a protected environment where lean methods can operate w/o being crushed by corporate antibodies.
M|The |**Sa|**
M|The |tx|1. Dedicated team (3-7 people), not part-time contributors
M|The |tx|2. Separate budget w/ metered funding tied to learning milestones
M|The |tx|3. Authority to experiment w/ real cs (within defined guardrails)
M|The |tx|4. Reports to a single executive sponsor, not a committee
M|The |tx|5. Immune from normal planning cycles, quarterly reviews, and approval chains for small expenditures
M|Adap|tx|\| Corporate Constraint \| Lean Adaptation \|
M|Adap|tx|\|---------------------\|----------------\|
M|Adap|tx|\| br risk \| Use a separate br or "labs" label for experiments \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Legal/compliance rv \| Pre-ap experiment templates; legal reviews for categories, not individual experiments \|
M|Adap|tx|\| IT infrastructure requirements \| Use external cloud services; sandbox data separately from production \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Budget approval cycles \| Secure a quarterly innovation budget; spend authority within that budget is delegated to the team \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Stakeholder management \| Monthly innovation reviews w/ standardized reporting (not ad-hoc presentations) \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Existing cs relationships \| tst w/ non-st accounts first; get explicit opt-in for experimental features \|
M|Corp|tx|\| Anti-Pattern \| Why It Kills Innovation \| Fix \|
M|Corp|tx|\|-------------\|------------------------\|-----\|
M|Corp|tx|\| Innovation theater \| Lots of activity, no validated learning \| Require experiment results, not activity reports \|
M|Corp|tx|\| sc metrics tied to rv too early \| Forces premature scaling of unvalidated ideas \| Use innovation accounting metrics for the first 6-12 months \|
M|Corp|tx|\| "Not invented here" syndrome \| Team dismisses external signals and cs feedback \| Mandate cs interviews and competitive al \|
M|Corp|tx|\| Pilot-to-pd gap \| Successful pilots die bc no path to integration exists \| Define the integration path before starting the pilot \|
M|Corp|tx|\| Consensus-driven decisions \| Every stakeholder must agree before testing \| Designate a single decision maker for the innovation team \|
M|Lean|tx|Lean methods apply not just to new pd but to individual features within existing pd. Every new feature is a hypothesis abt what cs want.
M|Feat|**St|State the hypothesis**
M|Feat|tx|"We believe that [feature] will cause [metric] to improve by [amount] for [us segment] bc [reason]."
M|Feat|**St|ds the smallest tst**
M|Feat|tx|\| tst tp \| When to Use \| bd Time \|
M|Feat|tx|\|-----------\|-------------\|------------\|
M|Feat|tx|\| Fake door tst \| Gauge demand before building \| 1 day \|
M|Feat|tx|\| Wizard of Oz \| tst the exp before building the engine \| 3-5 days \|
M|Feat|tx|\| Limited rollout \| tst w/ a small percentage of us \| 1-2 weeks \|
M|Feat|tx|\| A/B tst \| Compare new feature against current exp \| 1-3 weeks \|
M|Feat|tx|\| Time-limited pilot \| tst w/ a specific segment for a fixed period \| 2-4 weeks \|
M|Feat|**St|Set sc criteria before launch**
M|Feat|**St|Measure and decide**
M|Feat|- Fe|roll out to all us
M|Feat|- Fe|iterate and retest
M|Feat|- Fe|kill it and move on
M|Feat|Defi|
M|Feat|it|[ ] Adoption below X% after Y weeks of availability
M|Feat|it|[ ] No measurable impact on target metric after full rollout
M|Feat|it|[ ] Increases support tickets w/o corresponding engagement increase
M|Feat|it|[ ] Negative impact on core metrics (retention, activation, rv)
M|Feat|it|[ ] Maintenance cost exceeds value delivered
M|Feat|tx|Most teams add features but never remove them. This creates bloat. Lean teams treat features as experiments that must earn their place.
M|Lean|Hard|longer bd cycles, higher iteration costs, and physical supply chain constraints. But lean principles still apply.
M|Hard|tx|\| Lean Principle \| Software Implementation \| Hardware Adaptation \|
M|Hard|tx|\|---------------\|------------------------\|---------------------\|
M|Hard|tx|\| MVP \| Landing page or single-feature app \| 3D-printed prototype, vd demonstration, Kickstarter cg \|
M|Hard|tx|\| bd-Measure-Learn loops \| Weekly cycles \| Monthly cycles (still faster than traditional 18-month dv) \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Continuous dpl \| dp code multiple times per day \| Rapid prototyping w/ ds iterations every 2-4 weeks \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Small batches \| Single feature releases \| Small production runs (50-100 units) before mass manufacturing \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Pivot \| Change pd direction \| Change form factor, target cs, or use case \|
M|Hard|tx|1. **Validate demand before prototyping.** Use vd MVPs, landing pages, or crowdfunding to confirm people want the pd before spending on tooling.
M|Hard|tx|2. **Prototype w/ off-the-shelf cp.** Use Arduino, Raspberry Pi, 3D printing, and existing enclosures to tst functionality before custom engineering.
M|Hard|tx|3. **tst w/ small production runs.** Manufacture 50-100 units before committing to mass production. Use these for real-world testing w/ cs.
M|Hard|tx|4. **Separate the software from the hardware.** Where possible, make the software updateable even if the hardware is fixed. This enables iteration on the exp w/o re-manufacturing.
M|Hard|tx|5. **ds for modularity.** Modular designs allow cp-level iteration w/o redesigning the entire pd.
M|Hard|tx|\| Phase \| Duration \| Activity \| Output \|
M|Hard|tx|\|-------\|----------\|----------\|--------\|
M|Hard|tx|\| Demand validation \| 2-4 weeks \| Landing page, vd, pre-orders \| Evidence of demand \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Functional prototype \| 4-8 weeks \| Off-the-shelf cp, 3D printing \| Working prototype for 10-20 us \|
M|Hard|tx|\| us testing \| 4-8 weeks \| Place prototypes w/ real us \| Usage data, feedback, iteration list \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Small batch production \| 8-12 weeks \| Manufacture 50-100 units \| Real-world perf data \|
M|Hard|tx|\| Mass production decision \| 1 week \| rv all data \| Go/no-go on mass production \|
M|Lean|Serv|the pd is delivered by people, making iteration almost instantaneous.
M|Serv|**Ph|Define the Service MVP**
M|Serv|it|Deliver the service to 3-5 clients manually
M|Serv|it|Do not bd a platform, booking sy, or br
M|Serv|it|Focus entirely on delivering value and observing the client exp
M|Serv|**Ph|Systematize What Works**
M|Serv|it|Identify the parts of the service that clients value most
M|Serv|it|cr standard operating procedures for hi-value activities
M|Serv|it|Eliminate or reduce lo-value activities
M|Serv|it|cr templates and checklists
M|Serv|**Ph|Scale Selectively**
M|Serv|it|Hire or contract for the highest-value, most systematized parts
M|Serv|it|Continue delivering hi-touch, variable parts manually
M|Serv|it|Only bd technology when manual processes become the bottleneck
M|Serv|tx|\| Experiment \| Method \| What You Learn \|
M|Serv|tx|\|-----------\|--------\|----------------\|
M|Serv|tx|\| Value-based pricing \| Quote different prices to different (similar) clients \| Price sensitivity and perceived value ceiling \|
M|Serv|tx|\| Tiered packages \| Offer basic/standard/premium \| Which value cp clients prioritize \|
M|Serv|tx|\| Retainer vs project \| Offer both to similar clients \| Client preference for commitment level \|
M|Serv|tx|\| Money-back guarantee \| Offer a satisfaction guarantee \| Confidence in delivery and client risk perception \|
M|Lean|Nonp|will this program achieve its intended impact? Lean methods help them tst interventions quickly and allocate resources to what works.
M|Adap|tx|\| Startup Concept \| Nonprofit Translation \|
M|Adap|tx|\|----------------\|----------------------\|
M|Adap|tx|\| cs \| Beneficiary (the person served) and donor/funder (the person who pays) \|
M|Adap|tx|\| rv \| Impact metrics (outcomes achieved) and funding secured \|
M|Adap|tx|\| pd-mk fit \| Program-beneficiary fit (the program achieves intended outcomes) \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Growth engine \| Funding engine (how the organization sustains itself) \|
M|Adap|tx|\| Pivot \| Program redesign or population change \|
M|Adap|tx|\| MVP \| Pilot program w/ 10-20 beneficiaries \|
M|Nonp|tx|1. **Define the theory of change.** What specific intervention will cause what specific outcome for what specific population?
M|Nonp|tx|2. **Identify leap-of-faith assumptions.** What must be true for this intervention to work?
M|Nonp|tx|3. **ds a pilot.** Deliver the intervention to a small group. Measure actual outcomes, not just outputs.
M|Nonp|tx|4. **Distinguish outputs from outcomes.**
M|Nonp|- Ou|100 people attended the workshop
M|Nonp|- Ou|40 of those people applied the skills within 30 days
M|Nonp|- Im|20 of those people saw measurable improvement in the target area
M|Nonp|tx|5. **Iterate based on outcomes.** If outcomes are below targets, redesign the intervention. If outcomes are strong, scale.
M|Gove|tx|\| Traditional Government \| Lean Government \|
M|Gove|tx|\|----------------------\|-----------------\|
M|Gove|tx|\| Multi-year planning process \| 90-day experiment cycles \|
M|Gove|tx|\| Large-scale program launch \| Small pilot w/ 100-500 participants \|
M|Gove|tx|\| Measure compliance and outputs \| Measure outcomes and beneficiary exp \|
M|Gove|tx|\| Evaluation after 3-5 years \| Evaluation after each 90-day cycle \|
M|Gove|tx|\| Fixed program ds \| Iterative program ds based on data \|
M|Univ|tx|1. **Start w/ the cs.** Understand the problem before designing the solution.
M|Univ|tx|2. **tst assumptions, not ideas.** Identify what must be true and validate it.
M|Univ|tx|3. **Minimize time to learn.** Speed through the learning loop is the fundamental advantage.
M|Univ|tx|4. **Use actionable metrics.** Measure what informs decisions, not what feels good.
M|Univ|tx|5. **Make pivot decisions based on evidence.** Not politics, not sunk costs, not ego.
M|Cont|tx|\| Context Variable \| Adaptation \|
M|Cont|tx|\|-----------------\|------------\|
M|Cont|tx|\| hi regulation (healthcare, fi) \| Pre-ap experiment categories w/ legal/compliance; longer cycles but still experimental \|
M|Cont|tx|\| Long sales cycles (enterprise B2B) \| Use letters of intent and paid pilots as validation signals; monthly instead of weekly loops \|
M|Cont|tx|\| Physical pd (hardware, CPG) \| Front-load demand validation; use rapid prototyping for solution validation \|
M|Cont|tx|\| Two-sided markets (marketplaces) \| Validate each side separately; often need concierge for supply side first \|
M|Cont|tx|\| Network-dependent pd (sl) \| tst w/ small, dense communities; do not try to cr a network at scale from day one \|
M|Cont|tx|\| hi-stakes decisions (medical, legal) \| Use simulation and role-playing before real-world testing; involve domain experts in experiment ds \|
M|Cont|| Lo|paper prototypes, in-person observations, phone surveys \|
M|Cont|The |what is the fastest, cheapest way to learn whether this assumption is true? The answer changes by context. The question does not.